let’s plot for only 5 row readings All Variables (i.e. columns will be plotted)

library(ggplot2)
tsla[1:5,] %>%
  select(-Volume) %>%
  melt(id="Date") %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=Date, y=value,col=variable)) +
  geom_line(aes(x=Date, y=value,col=variable, group=variable))

include the alpha parameter - this influences the level of transparency (0 minimum - 1.0 maximum)

tsla[1:5,] %>%
  select(-Volume) %>%
  melt(id="Date") %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=Date, y=value,col=variable), alpha=0.5) +

Now we will create a dataframe without the Volume variable

tsla_vals = tsla %>%
  select(-Volume) # -"NA"

GET THE YEAR ONLY FROM DATE COLUMN 1. Create a new variable/column called year. 2. Extract the year component from the full date Note: day - %d …. month - %M … year - %Y 3. Then group by year so that we can perform the final step: 4. Calculate the mean price for each variable by using the summarize function from tidyverse

We will then plot our findings

tsla_vals_sum_years =tsla_vals %>% 
  mutate(year=format(Date,"%Y")) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(mean(Open),mean(Close),mean(High),mean(Low),mean(`Adj Close`))

#rename variables(columns)
names(tsla_vals_sum_years) = c("year","sum_open","sum_close","sum_high","sum_low","sum_adjClose")

tsla_vals_sum_years %>% melt(id="year") %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=year, y=value,col=variable), alpha=0.5) +
  geom_line(aes(x=year, y=value,col=variable, group=variable), alpha=0.8)

The results could be linked to news events relating to Tesla at that particular period in time. https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-musk-timeline/timeline-main-events-in-teslas-history-as-a-public-company-idUSKBN1KV2A0

Another example of extracting specific dates GET 2016 opening and closing values

tsla_open_close_2016 = tsla %>% 
  select(Date, Open,Close) %>%
  mutate(year=format(Date,"%Y")) %>%
  filter(year=="2016")
